    "Unfortunately, this bound is useless in practice, as the right-hand side depends on the unknown distribution of the observations via the variance term V.",
    "It turns out that it is possible to upper bound the term E θ∼ρ [V(θ)] by an empirical variance term to obtain a so-called empirical PAC-Bayes-Bernstein bound (Seldin et al., 2012a; Tolstikhin and Seldin, 2013)."
